1 What is Data Programming?

Programming is a practice of using programming language to design, perform and evaluate tasks using a computer. These tasks include:

  • Computation
  • Data collection
  • Data management
  • Data visualization
  • Data modeling

Data programming is a programming practice that focuses on data. It works and evolves with data. In this series, we learn how to design data programs using R (with some Python). Both languages are high-level, interpreted languages that are also objected-oriented and functional. R is the primary language used in this series since it is simple but with a full list of functionalities available through a great number of packages. RStudio is the IDE used and it is free and available in most of the operating systems. It is also available in RStudio Cloud.

2 Why Data Programming?

  1. Data programming is all about data
  2. Data programming is for all to understand
  • Programmers tend to adapt other programs without understanding how they work and use reverse engineering to figure out what the modules and functions are for.
  • Data programming starts from the fundamentals, communicates the purpose of the program and its goal-oriented.
  1. Data programming is for development (v.0, v.1)
  2. Data programs should be incremental with version control.
  3. Data programming is for communication
  • Write the program for the first audience: the future you
  • Write the program for others: students and collaborators

3 Hands-on workshop: K-nearest Neighbor (KNN)

KNN classifier first identifies the \(K\) points in the training data that are closest to \(x_0\), represented by N0. It then estimates the conditional probability for class j as the fraction of points in (N_)0 whose response values equal \(j\)

# Create training data set
# Note: no reshuffling.  Why? 
train=(Year<2005)

# Create testing data sets
Smarket.2005=Smarket[!train,]
Direction.2005=Direction[!train]

library(class)

train.X=cbind(Lag1,Lag2)[train,]
test.X=cbind(Lag1,Lag2)[!train,]
train.Direction=Direction[train]
set.seed(1)

# Running K-nearest Neighbor 
# k-nearest neighbour classification for test set from training set. 
# For each row of the test set, the k nearest (in Euclidean distance) 
# training set vectors are found, and the classification is decided by 
# majority vote, with ties broken at random. 
# If there are ties for the kth nearest vector, all candidates are 
# included in the vote.

knn.pred=knn(train.X,test.X,train.Direction,k=1)

# Confusion matrix
table(knn.pred,Direction.2005)
##         Direction.2005
## knn.pred Down Up
##     Down   43 58
##     Up     68 83
(83+43)/252
## [1] 0.5
knn.pred=knn(train.X,test.X,train.Direction,k=3)
table(knn.pred,Direction.2005)
##         Direction.2005
## knn.pred Down Up
##     Down   48 54
##     Up     63 87
# What is the chance the stock is going up?
mean(knn.pred==Direction.2005)
## [1] 0.5357143
